Clearly not. The creature merely hissed and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she nearly lost her grip on its overly smooth scales.
"WHAT DO YOU KILL THEM WITH?", shouted Nyssi.
"AIM AT THEIR HEADS!"
"THAT'S NOT GOING TO BE EASY!"
Thassalin exhaled, then circled around to get closer to the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed him, somewhat panicked when a flash of fire struck her from behind. The creature hadn't noticed that she was no longer alone. Her panic increased when Thassalin slowed down, then violently struck her head with his tail, causing her to deviate from her path.
Growling and hissing, the creature gained altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster was sucking in the light of the sky and replacing it with a perpetual cloud of night.
With no visibility left, Thassalin tried to retreat, but grazed the tops of the trees before crashing into the clearing. As if she had known exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud in her wake.
"Kayel!" exclaimed Tenuk as he emerged from the cloud and began flying in circles, trying to spot Nyssi and Thassalin below in the darkness. "What do we do, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Down below, Nyssi got up as best she could. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, unnatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. The same could not be said for Thassalin, who lay on a mound, leaning against the only tree that had not bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try and reach Thassalin, but she could not see more than two meters ahead of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed by the impious shadows. And within those shadows, something was screaming.
An horrible club-shaped tail swings down beside Nyssi, knocking her flat. However, she noticed that the tail was swishing around without aiming at her. The creature, from what Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and scratching at the shadows it had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, striking the monster and disorienting it.
A sudden gunshot rang out, and the monster collapsed silently, lifeless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing on the creature was Kayel, holding the rifle and breathing heavily.
"It's... the weirdest shadow jump I've ever done... Thanto kat'olon..." gasped Kayel. His eyes shimmered with a dark glow, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow hue.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, as most people considered them impious and rather terrifying. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed surprised as well.
"You're all right?" Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something. It'll be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work as Tenuk forced his way to land beside him, returning to his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was black as coal and slimy, but the slime continued to stick to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what that thing was, something howled and sprang from a nearby bush. However, the creature didn't have time to reach them, as a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, throwing it at Nyssi's feet. Taking no chances, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature instantly.
"Oops...", mumbled Retvik from the driver's seat, then awkwardly turned off the engine and jumped out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you okay?"
"You practically missed all the action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"I've been abandoned by all of you," sighed Retvik. "Just how fast could I have come here?" "May I ask what these despicable things are?"
Fortunately, Retvik's question received an answer from Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was all cut up and scratched everywhere and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't look too seriously injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"T-You mean... the horrible god-monster that we... helped kill?", stuttered Tenuk.
"YES. ABSOLUTELY. THERE MAY BE OTHERS, BUT I WASN'T ABLE TO AIM FOR THEIR HEADS. I'M MISSING A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE ISN'T FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin approached Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, KID. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST LESS MURDEROUS AND LESS CAPABLE OF KILLING UNIVERSES."
"Euh... thanks... I guess," said Kayel with a shrug. "So, are we done here?"
Nissy shrugged, then grabbed her camera to photograph the creatures, now clearly dead. She then took out her favorite dagger, the one of the god of death, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns before moving on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures caught fire and quickly turned into piles of ashes. The same thing happened to the horns that Nissy had cut off.
"Well... it's both convenient and not convenient at all," she sighed. "At least, I still have the photos..."
